I personally did a bit of an experiment over a three week period.( a school week- or 5 days, which then the weekend, Saturday - Sunday, are the "test" days)

Basically for each week I would consume only the most specific food groups for five days then exercise on Saturday and Sunday causing myself to sweat. basically my test was to see if what I ate affected the smell of my sweat.

Week #1 - I consumed only food with highly concentrated sugar- e.g. - yams, bananas, carrots, flavored drinks
Result- sweat had an aroma of a sweetened nectar, similar to honey- had a watery viscosity.

Week #2 - consumed only food with lot of carbohydrates- e.g. breaded foods, and water
Result- sweat had aroma of beer or fermented wheat- had a almost greasy/ watery viscosity.

week #3 - consumed only foods sodium/salt- e.g. - nuts, soups, chips, crackers, anchovies
Result - Sweat had an average aroma - while the viscosity was extremely thin and very watery.

Yes, I know this was a very strange and gross experiment. But I had thought about this while exercising and decided to test it out due to the fact that it was a fascinating thing to do.

Come on guys, hear me out! I was thinking about this last night... So, if you were to eat human flesh, would it taste good or bad? Just hear me out! Taking time to really think about what you’re eating is connected to whether or not you’re living a happy life. That’s why I think it’s really important. So, there are animals that are carnivores, right? You know, like cats, lions and vultures. You won’t find meat from carnivores like that at a restaurant. Why is that? Because it’s too smelly to eat! It’s disgusting! Listen up guys! Cats are too disgusting to eat. Are we on the same page so far? On the other hand, have you ever heard of a fish called “sweetfish”? Sweetfish don’t eat bugs. They only eat algae. They’re vegetarian. Usually, fish guts are too bitter to eat, but sweetfish guts are delicious. It’s because they’re not carnivores. So with that logic in mind, all the meat we consider delicious is from herbivorous animals! Cows, pigs and chickens! The better their feed, the better they taste! Which leads us to this conclusion... wanna learn how to make lemon cake..? well its your lucky day
Ingredients:
1/2 pound (2 sticks) unsalted butter, at room temperature
2 1/2 cups granulated sugar, divided
4 extra-large eggs, at room temperature
1/3 cup grated lemon zest (6 to 8 large lemons)
3 cups flour
1/2 teaspoon baking powder
1/2 teaspoon baking soda
1 teaspoon kosher salt
3/4 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice, divided
3/4 cup buttermilk, at room temperature
1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
For the glaze:
2 cups confectioners' sugar, sifted
3 1/2 tablespoons freshly squeezed lemon juice
Instructions:
Step 1: Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F. Grease and flour 2 (8 1/2 by 4 1/4 by 2 1/2-inch) loaf pans. You may also line the bottom with parchment paper, if desired.
Step 2: Cream the butter and 2 cups granulated sugar in the bowl of an electric mixer fitted with the paddle attachment, until light and fluffy, about 5 minutes. With the mixer on medium speed, add the eggs, 1 at a time, and the lemon zest.
Step 3: Sift together the flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt in a bowl. In another bowl, combine 1/4 cup lemon juice, the buttermilk, and vanilla. Add the flour and buttermilk mixtures alternately to the batter, beginning and ending with the flour. Divide the batter evenly between the pans, smooth the tops, and bake for 45 minutes to 1 hour, until a cake tester comes out clean.
Step 4: Combine 1/2 cup granulated sugar with 1/2 cup lemon juice in a small saucepan and cook over low heat until the sugar dissolves. When the cakes are done, allow to cool for 10 minutes. Remove the cakes from the pans and set them on a rack set over a tray or sheet pan; spoon the lemon syrup over them. Allow the cakes to cool completely.
Step 5:For the glaze, combine the confectioners' sugar and the lemon juice in a bowl, mixing with a wire whisk until smooth. Pour over the tops of the cakes and allow the glaze to drizzle down the sides.

This is a paradox I've considered before which I call the "Cannibal's Paradox" since that's what gave me the idea; though it can apply to other topics that follow this logic.

Consider the question: "What does human flesh taste like?"
There are two primary ways you have of finding out the answer. You can eat human flesh to learn firsthand or you can ask someone/read the account of a someone who has already done so. In the case of the latter, you'll see that people who have eaten human flesh did so in a moment of psychosis or where they were otherwise not in their right mind. Indeed, the descriptions conflict with one another, and the parties involved admit to not being of sound mind in the moment. Therefore one cannot trust the accounts of these people. Thus in order to learn what human meat tastes like, you must taste it yourself. However most instances where you'd get the chance would involve illegal activity, and much of this would probably require you to also not be in your right mind. Thus the paradox is made evident. This is an experience which you cannot gain information about based on firsthand accounts because of the nature of the experience, and you similarly cannot experience it for yourself either because doing so would require you also be in a state where you could not trust your own senses.

Fun story: an escape attempt in Sierra Chica prison (Argentina) planned by 12 inmates (called the 12 Apostles by the press) startled a mutiny, in which they took hostages and liberated the rest of the inmates to roam freely within the prison. It lasted 8 days.
Turns out that most of the inmates used the mutiny to take revenge on a pretty devastating group of inmates that acted as an "enforce task" for corrupt cops, and killed them. Because almost everything within the prison was abandoned by the orders of a judge, the inmates could do almost anything (even attempt to escape via underground tunnels, which failed) and so the 12 Apostles took charge of the situation and started cooking for the rest of the prison's population and hostages. They used the kitchen's ovens to burn the bodies of this "enforce task" that was killed by the rest of the inmates.
But the horror (I honestly find it strangely interesting, not horrifying) doesn't stop there, they used the ASS of one of the dead inmates (not part of the "enforce task", but was killed because some inmates thought he was an undercover cop; poor guy was literally mental) and made empanadas which then used to fed the hostages.

A few points I want to make: almost everything I know about it is from a book made by a journalist who interviewed one of the Apostles (he luckily made it out of prison and is living a kinda normal life). The 12 apostles weren't highly organized, but a group of 4 or 5 inmates who wanted to escape and had to accept other inmates that heard what they were planning so they didn't snitch to the guards. All hostages were freed at the end of the mutiny (none of them were hurt).

So, one question comes to mind, as I've seen in some comments, why don't we eat our dead? Well, taking the complex social and political part, it is, at least for me, a simple question to answer:
  We are one of the most inefficient animals in the "transforming food into nutrients" "business". See, chickens on need to eat a few grains per day, and when they're dead we've got almost 2 kilos of meat, plus the eggs in her life time. A human needs to eat more than 5 chickens a month just to be (barely) alive. And I'm not counting on the liters of water, the vegetables, fruits, milk, etc. And given that in a helthy 100kg adult 21kg are blood and bones(that technically are edible, but not optimal), you had all that work, all that investment, just to get 89kg of meat. Considering that a healthy adult eats 175g of meat everyday, give it or take, a single human would feed 4 people for 127 days. In comparison, a bull (the weight of his eskeleton was removes) gives you 210 kilos of meat, which woud feed those 4 people for 400 days.
  Although I couldn't find numbers, it is safe to assume bulls are more effecient, since they're vegetarian, which means, secondary in the food chain, or, more efficient absortion of energy. What would be a better way to recycle our dead? I say lets bury them so their corpses fertilize land which we can use to produce plants, and, why not, bulls and chickens.
  Another question comes to mind: why I did this small research? I've got bored.

But the brain is made to find the prospect of cannibalism (more specifically for humans) quite vile and revolting to tell our bodies not to try it ourselves, for the same reason that the brain recognizing an odor tells the body to move away from the area because it is potentially harmful.

What we find gross, taboo, or disturbing is our brains telling us not to go near or attempt as it can be harmful. Of course, we can simply override that signal of repugnance and do it anyway, but it is true that some people may have developed by birth or genetics to have less signals like these telling to be disgusted, and partake of the deed, which may explain why one may watch this video and be disturbed, while another maybe unphased.

In the end, or bodies are constantly alerting us by giving us the emotions of revulsion, disgust, disturbance to tell us to leave the area, but for all of those emotions of sickness, we also get love, admiration, soothe, pleasant, that tells us that we should continue and it may be beneficial.

Of course, our brain isn't perfect, because if it was, it would be telling us that broccoli would taste like a slice of pizza and the pizza would taste like grass. The brain can be tricked and manipulated, but the senses it gives us can truly reveal the authenticates of a substance, whether it be the pleasant smell of a glass of soda, or the vicious sting of a vial of poison.

These senses help us, the tell us what is dangerous, or what is helpful, when our rooms need to be cleaned, or when we should wash our clothes, what foods to digest, and what objects we should steer clear of.

We need our brain, because as long as we are moving, we will always be on a journey of scavenging and hiding from the life around us, so you should be proud of, and take care of, the brain you have because, it is probably the best personal computer you're ever going to have.

A pair of Swedish comedians did something similar in the early 00's. Fredrik & Philip, a popular comedy duo that has somewhat specialized in finding odd people, habits and things around the world once took a biopsy of Fredriks buttock and fried it. Then they both shared a piece of it each. It was just a tiny piece, but enough to create an outcry from angry soccer moms, who believed they were teaching kids cannibalism.

The funny part about the story is that they have never been a kids show, they often have adult themes, it was shown at 10pm and the show they were doing was to show that humans are edible, but not that special. They too found that it tasted a bit like veel and went on to recommend any potential cannibal to kill a young cow instead of a human.

Is it really that immoral and is it really the comedian's fault if kids see it, when they've taken every precaution to make sure that they don't on their end? Whose fault was it, the moms that let their kids watch a show that clearly wasn't for kids, or the comedians that made the show?
